    <preface>
      <p>Annex 1</p>
    </preface>
    <mainBody>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>TRANSPOSITION NOTE FOR COUNCIL DIRECTIVE 2001/110/EC RELATING TO HONEY (AS AMENDED)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>(DIRECTIVE TO DOMESTIC REGULATIONS)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>This Note shows how the requirements of Council Directive 2001/110/EC relating to honey (“the Honey Directive”), as last amended by Directive 2014/63/EU of the European Parliament and the Council, have been implemented in England. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>As well as the provisions of the Honey Directive, Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 of the European Parliament and of the Council on the provision of food information to consumers applies to the products regulated by the Honey Directive. The name of food provisions in Article 17 of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 will apply. The names of products prescribed by the Honey Directive are legal names for the purposes of Article 17(1) of the Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011. The requirements relating to the availability, placement and presentation of mandatory particulars will apply to the particulars that are mandatory under the Honey Directive. Article 8 of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 contains provisions regulating the information that businesses must provide when selling food to other businesses. This includes, for example, an obligation to provide sufficient information to those businesses to enable mandatory food information to be provided to the final consumer and mass caterers when food is eventually sold to them. Enforcement provisions relating to the provisions of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 are contained in the Food Information Regulations 2014 (S.I. 2014/1855).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Approach of the Regulations</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Honey Directive was originally implemented in England by the Honey (England) Regulations 2003 (S.I. 2003/2243) (“the 2003 Regulations”). However, the 2003 Regulations have been amended by the Honey (Amendment) (England) Regulations 2005 (S.I. 2005/1920) and the Food Information Regulations 2014. Now that the Honey Directive has been amended (by Directive 2014/63/EU), it has decided to replace the 2003 Regulations with updated domestic Regulations which implement the Honey Directive, as amended by Directive 2014/63/EU. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <content>
          <p>The requirements of the Honey Directive, as amended, will be implemented by the Honey (England) Regulations 2015 (“the 2015 Regulations”) as follows:</p>
          <table uk:widths="1.49in 4.71in 4.26in 4.23in">
            <tr>
              <th>
                <p />
                <p>Article in the Honey Directive</p>
                <p />
              </th>
              <th>
                <p />
                <p>Objective</p>
              </th>
              <th>
                <p />
                <p>Provision in the Honey (England) Regulations 2015</p>
              </th>
              <th>
                <p />
                <p>Comment</p>
              </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 1, first sentence)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Specifies the products to which the Directive applies</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>No specific provision</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>This forms of the basis of the whole of the 2015 Regulations – it runs throughout the provisions. </p>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 1, second sentence</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Requirement for the regulated products to meet the criteria set out in Annex II</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 16</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, introductory words</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Application of Directive 2000/13/EC</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>For the most part nothing is needed.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 4</p>
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p><b>Direct applicability of the provisions of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011</b></p>
                <p />
                <p>Directive 2000/13/EC was repealed by Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 of the European Parliament and of the Council on the provision of food information to consumers on 13th December 2014.</p>
                <p />
                <p>By virtue of Article 53(2) of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011, references to Directive 2000/13/EC in the Honey Directive are now treated as references to Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011. </p>
                <p />
                <p>The provisions of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 are directly applicable. They are enforced, in England, under the Food Information Regulations 2014 (S.I. 2014/1855).</p>
                <p />
                <p />
                <p><b>Limited scope</b></p>
                <p>The opening words of Article 2 of the Honey Directive state that Article 2000/13/EC is to apply to the Annex I products. The 2000/13/EC reference must, as explained above, be construed as a 1169/2011 reference now. </p>
                <p />
                <p>As Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 only applies (at least for the most part) to food intended for supply to a final consumer or mass caterer, then (because of the opening words of Article 2 of the Honey Directive) so should our domestic legislation implementing the Honey Directive. This implemented by regulation 4 and this approach to scope mirrors the approach taken in the Honey (England) Regulations 2003. </p>
                <p />
                <p>Not all of the provisions of the Honey Directive are only intended to apply the food intended for supply to a final consumer or mass caterers. Some provisions are of wider scope. This is why the scope provision in regulation 4(1) of the 2015 Regulations is limited to the provisions of the 2015 Regulations listed in (a) to (c) of that paragraph.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 1</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Restricting the use of the term “honey” as a product name</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 6(1), (2) and (3)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 2, first sub-paragraph, first sentence</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulating the use of product names – requiring the names to be used for regulated products and prohibiting those names from being used for other products</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p><b>For blossom honey and nectar honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 7(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For honeydew honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 8(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For comb honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 9(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For chunk honey and cut comb in honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 10(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For drained honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 11(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For extracted honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 12(1) and (3)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p><b>For pressed honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 13(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For filtered honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 14(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For baker’s honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 15(1) and (2)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 2, first sub-paragraph, second sentence</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Permitting the use of the simple product name “honey” in the case of some of the regulated products</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p><b>For blossom honey and nectar honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 7(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For honeydew honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 8(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For drained honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 11(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For extracted honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 12(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For pressed honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 13(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 2, second sub-paragraph, paragraph (a) </p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Additional labelling requirement for baker’s honey </p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 15(4)</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 2, second sub-paragraph, paragraph (b)</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Allowing supplemental information to be provided relating to floral or vegetable origin, regional, territorial or topographical origin and specific quality criteria but not in the case of filtered honey and baker’s honey</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 17(2), (3), (4) and (5)</p>
                <p />
                <p>Filtered honey exclusion:</p>
                <p>Regulation 14(3)</p>
                <p />
                <p>Baker’s honey exclusion:</p>
                <p>Regulation 15(3)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 3, first sentence</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Permitting the use of the simple product name “honey” in the product name of a compound food in which baker’s honey has been used as an ingredient </p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 15(6)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 3, second sentence</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Requirement that baker’s honey is identified as ‘baker’s honey’ in the list of ingredients of a compound food in a case where baker’s honey has been used as an ingredient in the compound food but the name ‘honey’ is used in the product name of the compound food  (as permitted by the first sentence of point 3 of Article 2)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 15(7)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 4(a)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Mandatory requirement for an indication of the country or countries of origin of honey to be given on the label </p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 17(1)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 4(b)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Provision requiring the mandatory country of origin indication to be considered as a mandatory indication under Article 3 of  Directive 2000/13/EC and for the relevant provisions of Directive 2000/13/EC to be applied accordingly</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need direct implementation in the 2015 Regulations themselves but regulation 21 of the 2015 Regulations, as read with paragraphs 1 and 2 of Schedule 3 to those Regulations, makes a consequential amendment to the Food Information Regulations 2014 to implement the provision. </p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Directive 2000/13/EC was repealed by Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011.</p>
                <p />
                <p>By virtue of Article 53(2) of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011, references to Directive 2000/13/EC in the Honey Directive are now treated as references to Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011. </p>
                <p />
                <p>The provisions in Article 12 Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 relating to the availability and placement of mandatory food information, and the provisions of Article 13(1) of that Regulation relating to the presentation of mandatory food information, apply, by virtue of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011,  to the presentation of mandatory food information. </p>
                <p />
                <p>‘Mandatory food information’ is defined as meaning ‘the particulars that are required to be provided to the final consumer by Union provisions’. These will include the country of origin indication that is required to be provided under point 4(a) of Article 2 of the Honey Directive. </p>
                <p />
                <p>Enforcement provisions enabling compliance with Articles 12 and 13(1) of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 to be enforced in England are contained in the Food Information Regulations 2014. </p>
                <p />
                <p />
                <p />
                <p>This is the position for all mandatory food information. </p>
                <p />
                <p>However, there is an additional element in relation to the country of origin information required by the Honey Directive. Not only must that country of origin information be treated as ‘mandatory food information’, it must be treated as if it was mandatory food information required by Article 9 of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 (in succession to Article 3 of Directive 2000/13/EC).  This makes a difference when it comes to the minimum font size that must be used for that country of origin information.</p>
                <p />
                <p>The 2015 Regulations amend the Food Information Regulations 2014 so  that the country of origin indication must is treated in the same way as mandatory particulars required by Article 9(1). This means that the minimum font size provisions in Article 13(2) and (3) of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 apply to them. The consequential amendments made by regulation 21 of the 2015 Regulations as read with paragraphs 1 and 2 of Schedule 3 to the Regulations, have this effect.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 2, point 5</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Exclusion of pollen from the definition of ingredient set out in point (f) of Article 2(2) of Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 of the European Parliament and of the Council.</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 3(1)  - definition of “ingredient”</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 3</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Requirement for indication of the full product name to be given on bulk containers, packs and trade documents in the case of baker’s honey and filtered honey</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p><b>For filtered honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 14(4)</p>
                <p />
                <p><b>For baker’s honey:</b></p>
                <p>Regulation 15(5)</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Please also see the supporting definitions of “bulk containers”, “packs” and “trade documents” in regulation 3(1).</p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 4(1)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Commission power to make implementing acts relating to methods of analysis to verify whether honey is compliant with the provisions of the Honey Directive</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need transposition – the Commission has not made any relevant implementing acts</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Member States are required to comply with method of analysis provisions in Article 4(1) until the Commission adopts implementing acts. </p>
                <p />
                <p>Article 11  of Regulation (EC) No 882/2004 of the European Parliament and of the Council on official controls performed to ensure the verification of compliance with feed and food law etc. also contains methods of analysis provisions and is directly applicable.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 4(2)</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Commission power to make delegated acts</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need to be transposed  into domestic legislation</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 5</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Prohibition on national provisions not provided for by the Honey Directive</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The 2015 Regulations do not contain any substantive national provisions not provided for by the Honey Directive.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The 2015 Regulations contain additional provisions concerning the enforcement of the provisions in the Honey Directive. Those type of national provisions are not prohibited by Article 5 of the Honey Directive and are required in order to give proper effect to the Honey Directive.</p>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 6</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Conditions applying to the Commission power to make delegated acts </p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need to be transposed  into domestic legislation</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 7</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Imposition of an obligation on the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health to assist the Commission in the process of adopting implementing acts</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need to be transposed  into domestic legislation</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 8</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Repeal of Directive 74/409/EEC</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need to be transposed  into domestic legislation</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The references to the Honey Directive in the 2015 Regulations are references to Directive 2001/110/EC.</p>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 9, first sub-paragraph</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Imposition of obligation on Member States to implement the provisions of the Directive</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The 2015 Regulations implement Directive 2001/110/EC, as amended by Directive 2014/63/EU.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The Honey Directive was previously implemented by the Honey (England) Regulations 2003. </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 9, second and third sub-paragraphs</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Application of transitional provisions</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 22 contains transitional provisions in line with Article 2 and 3 of Directive 2014/63/EC.</p>
                <p />
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 9, fourth sub-paragraph</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Imposition of obligation on Member States for the measure implementing the Honey Directive to contain or be accompanied by a reference to the Honey Directive</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>The first paragraph of  the Explanatory Note for the 2015 Regulations contains a statement that the Regulations implement the Honey Directive.</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 10</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Entry into force provisions</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Regulation 1(1) provides that the 2015 Regulations come into force on 24th June 2015. </p>
                <p />
                <p>The 2015 Regulations revoke the 2003 Regulations on that date.</p>
                <p />
                <p>By virtue of Article 2 of Directive 2014/63/EU, the amendments effected by Directive 2014/63/EU must be implemented by 24th June 2015.</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Article 11</p>
                <p />
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Addressed to Member States </p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
                <p>Does not need to be transposed  into domestic legislation.</p>
              </td>
              <td>
                <p />
              </td>
            </tr>
